---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
const repo = "https://github.com/ellisgarver/macro-narrative-dynamics";
---

<Base title="research" active="research">
  <p class="eyebrow reveal">the research</p>
  <h1 class="reveal">what this project is built on</h1>
  <p class="lede reveal">
    the idea behind the tool, the literature and work which surrounds it, and what it was built for.
  </p>

  <section class="section reveal">
    <p class="eyebrow">the goal</p>
    <h2>a tool for reading the recent past</h2>
    <p>
      built as an educational and historical-analysis tool,
      walk back through fifteen years of macro-financial discourse and watch how
      specific stories — the 2013 taper tantrum, the transitory-inflation debate,
      the 2023 soft-landing turn — emerged, took hold, peaked and faded, in the
      words of the institutions that shaped them. or just keep an eye out for how the most
      recent stories are turning out.
    </p>
    <p>
      the aim is to make an abstract idea more concrete. Shiller's claim that narratives
      spread like contagions is easy to state and hard to feel. here you can see the
      curve, switch the lens, line it up against the markets, and judge the analogy
      for yourself. free and reproducible.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section reveal">
    <p class="eyebrow">the idea</p>
    <h2>contagious economic stories</h2>

    <figure class="idea-graphic reveal">
      <svg class="contagion" viewBox="0 0 320 130" aria-hidden="true">
        <line class="edge" x1="60" y1="65" x2="120" y2="30" />
        <line class="edge" x1="60" y1="65" x2="130" y2="100" />
        <line class="edge" x1="120" y1="30" x2="200" y2="42" />
        <line class="edge" x1="130" y1="100" x2="210" y2="92" />
        <line class="edge" x1="200" y1="42" x2="270" y2="65" />
        <line class="edge" x1="210" y1="92" x2="270" y2="65" />
        <circle class="node n-s" cx="60" cy="65" r="9" />
        <circle class="node n-a" cx="120" cy="30" r="8" />
        <circle class="node n-b" cx="130" cy="100" r="8" />
        <circle class="node n-c" cx="200" cy="42" r="8" />
        <circle class="node n-d" cx="210" cy="92" r="8" />
        <circle class="node n-e" cx="270" cy="65" r="9" />
      </svg>
      <figcaption class="sir-key">
        <span><i class="dot s"></i>susceptible</span>
        <span><i class="dot i"></i>infected</span>
        <span><i class="dot r"></i>recovered</span>
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      this project is framed around Robert Shiller's <em>Narrative Economics</em> (2017 AEA
      presidential address; 2019 book): economic stories spread through a population
      the way contagious diseases do — a story is "caught" from exposure, carried for
      a while, and eventually dropped, and its prevalence over time traces the same
      rise-and-fall shape as an outbreak. this project seeks to quantify that analogy.
    </p>
    <p>
      Shiller maps cleanly onto SIR compartments: people who have not yet
      encountered a story are <em>susceptible</em>, those actively repeating it are
      <em>infected</em>, and those who have moved on are <em>recovered</em>. the same
      mechanics that determine whether a disease takes off also determine whether a story does. specifically,
      we measure the lifecycle half of Shiller's claim —
      emergence, growth, peak, decay — using century-old models economists
      and epidemiologists share, applied to the volume of institutional
      macro writing rather than to surveys or social media.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section reveal">
    <p class="eyebrow">the grounding</p>
    <h2>field-standard, not hand-tuned</h2>
    <p>
      results are credible because nothing is tuned
      to make the output look better. every parameter in the pipeline is either a
      published library default or a value taken from the primary literature with a
      citation. where no field-accepted anchor existed, that knob was removed
      rather than guessed or predicted. there are no sensitivity sweeps, no thresholds nudged
      toward a nicer-looking chart, and crucially, nothing is ever adjusted to
      improve how well the system recovers known events. with no
      train/test split, no-tuning rule keeps the exercise honest.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      see the full methodology, with citations in
      <a href={`${repo}/blob/main/docs/METHODOLOGY.md`} target="_blank" rel="noopener">METHODOLOGY.md</a>
      from the repository.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section reveal">
    <p class="eyebrow">further reading</p>
    <h2>references &amp; related work</h2>
    <ul class="reading">
      <li>
        Shiller, R. J. (2017). “Narrative Economics.” <em>American Economic Review</em>, 107(4), 967–1004.
        <a href="https://doi.org/10.1257/aer.107.4.967" target="_blank" rel="noopener">doi.org/10.1257/aer.107.4.967</a>
      </li>
      <li>
        Shiller, R. J. (2019). <em>Narrative Economics: How Stories Go Viral and Drive Major Economic Events</em>. Princeton University Press.
      </li>
      <li>
        Goffman, W., &amp; Newill, V. A. (1964). “Generalization of Epidemic Theory: An Application to the Transmission of Ideas.” <em>Nature</em>, 204, 225–228.
      </li>
      <li>
        Daley, D. J., &amp; Kendall, D. G. (1965). “Stochastic Rumours.” <em>Journal of the Institute of Mathematics and Its Applications</em>, 1(1), 42–55.
      </li>
      <li>
        Kermack, W. O., &amp; McKendrick, A. G. (1927). “A Contribution to the Mathematical Theory of Epidemics.” <em>Proceedings of the Royal Society A</em>, 115(772), 700–721.
      </li>
      <li>
        Roos, M., &amp; Reccius, M. (2024). “Narratives in Economics.” <em>Journal of Economic Surveys</em>, 38(2), 303–341.
      </li>
      <li>
        Bybee, L., Kelly, B., Manela, A., &amp; Xiu, D. (2024). “Business News and Business Cycles.” <em>Journal of Finance</em>, 79(5), 3105–3147.
        <a href="https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13377" target="_blank" rel="noopener">doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13377</a>
      </li>
      <li>
        Hansen, S., McMahon, M., &amp; Prat, A. (2018). “Transparency and Deliberation within the FOMC: A Computational Linguistics Approach.” <em>Quarterly Journal of Economics</em>, 133(2), 801–870.
      </li>
      <li>
        Grootendorst, M. (2022). “BERTopic: Neural Topic Modeling with a Class-Based TF-IDF Procedure.”
        <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2203.05794" target="_blank" rel="noopener">arXiv:2203.05794</a>
      </li>
      <li>
        Project documentation —
        <a href={`${repo}/blob/main/docs/METHODOLOGY.md`} target="_blank" rel="noopener">METHODOLOGY.md</a>
        and
        <a href={`${repo}/blob/main/docs/related_work.md`} target="_blank" rel="noopener">related_work.md</a>.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  /* contagion motif: a small SIR spread that loops — one seed infects its
     neighbours, then everyone recovers. */
  .idea-graphic { margin: 1.2rem auto 1.4rem; max-width: 340px; text-align: center; }
  .contagion { width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }
  .edge { stroke: var(--line); stroke-width: 1.4; opacity: 0.5; }
  .node { fill: var(--faint); animation: infect 7.5s ease-in-out infinite; }
  @keyframes infect {
    0%, 8% { fill: var(--faint); }
    20% { fill: var(--ember); }
    42% { fill: var(--ember); }
    60%, 92% { fill: var(--growth); }
    100% { fill: var(--faint); }
  }
  .n-s { animation-delay: 0s; } .n-a { animation-delay: 0.7s; } .n-b { animation-delay: 0.9s; }
  .n-c { animation-delay: 1.5s; } .n-d { animation-delay: 1.7s; } .n-e { animation-delay: 2.4s; }
  .sir-key {
    display: flex; gap: 1.1rem; justify-content: center; flex-wrap: wrap;
    margin-top: 0.5rem; color: var(--muted); font-size: var(--fs-meta);
  }
  .sir-key span { display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.35rem; }
  .sir-key .dot { width: 0.6rem; height: 0.6rem; border-radius: 50%; display: inline-block; }
  .sir-key .s { background: var(--faint); }
  .sir-key .i { background: var(--ember); }
  .sir-key .r { background: var(--growth); }

  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
    .node { animation: none; fill: var(--growth); }
  }

  .reading {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 1.1rem 0 0;
    padding: 0;
  }
  .reading li {
    padding: 0.6rem 0 0.6rem 1.6rem;
    text-indent: -1.6rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--line);
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .reading li:first-child { border-top: none; }
  .reading a { color: var(--decay); word-break: break-word; }
</style>
